data.name: lblInstructions.Text
data.value: This compares running three processes in sequential order, in three discrete threads, and using the ThreadPool function QueueUserWorkItem to managed threads according to CPU availability. To fully see the differences, be sure to run each multiple times in different orders, with high CPU intense processes and without, noting the thread numbers each process uses and time each takes.

data.name: lblInstructions2.Text
data.value: This shows how how to use the Threading.Timer class to set up timed events (even on different time intervals as in the example.) Since the timers utilize the ThreadPool it is possible (though not always the case) for the events to use the same thread to process both events, instead of having two fully dedicated threads.

data.name: lblInstructions3.Text
data.value: This demonstrates how to use ThreadPool.RegisterWaitForSingleObject and synchronization objects Mutex, ManualResetEvent, and AutoResetEvent, to trigger functions on separate threads, as opposed to having dedicated threads with blocking.
